  "slug": "lamb-hotpot-with-kidneys",
  "title": "Lancashire Hotpot with Kidneys",
  "subtitle": "Braised lamb shoulder and kidneys under a potato crust, the classic Lancashire baked casserole",
  "excerpt": "Lancashire hotpot is a baked casserole of lamb and root vegetables topped with overlapping potato slices that brown to a crust. The kidneys are traditional and give the gravy a depth that lamb alone does not achieve. It requires 2 hours in the oven and almost no active work.",
  "type": "RECIPE",
  "sourceNotes": "Traditional Lancashire. Mrs Beeton, Book of Household Management (1861), Project Gutenberg #10136: hotpot from mutton and kidneys. Traditional Lancashire mill workers' dish. Elizabeth David, English Bread and Yeast Cookery (1977) and Jane Grigson, English Food (1974): regional British dishes.",
  "body": {
    "type": "doc",
    "content": [
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "The ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "Lancashire hotpot",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr5it0000074v41fxhkkxs"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " is assembled raw and cooked in one pot. There is no pre-browning of the meat: the lamb and vegetables are layered directly in the casserole with flour, stock, and aromatics, and the long bake in the oven does all the work.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Prepare the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "kidneys",
            "type": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "glossaryTooltip",
                "attrs": {
                  "termId": "cmpdr5itu000174v4cgpywc47"
                }
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "text": " carefully: the white suet core must be removed from each half before they go in. Left in, it gives a harsh bitterness to the gravy; removed, the kidneys add only depth and a faint irony richness.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
