      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Method",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Layer and assemble",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Heat the oven to 170°C (150°C fan). Dust the ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{lamb-shoulder}} of lamb shoulder",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{lamb-kidneys}} kidneys",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{plain-flour}} of flour",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and season well with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{sea-salt-flakes}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{black-pepper}}",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". In a large deep casserole, layer the meat with the onion, carrot, ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{bay-leaves}} of bay",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{thyme}} of thyme",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ". Pour over ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{stock-beef}} of stock",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": " and the Worcestershire sauce if using. Arrange the sliced potato in overlapping layers over the top, seasoning as you go. Brush with ",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": "{{unsalted-butter}} of melted butter",
            "type": "text"
          },
          {
            "text": ".",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 3
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Bake",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Cover the casserole tightly and bake for 1.5 hours. Uncover, increase the oven to 190°C (170°C fan), and bake for a further 30 minutes until the potato top is golden and the lamb is completely tender. Rest for 10 minutes before serving.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "troubleshooter",
        "attrs": {
          "rows": [
            {
              "fix": "Remove the lid and turn the oven up to 200°C for the last 20-25 minutes. Brush the potato with a little extra butter if it looks dry.",
              "cause": "Lid was not removed for the final stage, or oven not hot enough",
              "symptom": "Potato top is pale and soft, not golden"
            },
            {
              "fix": "The flour on the meat thickens the gravy during the long bake. Ensure it is well dusted. If still thin, pour the gravy into a small saucepan and reduce on the hob before serving.",
              "cause": "Too much stock, or the flour dusting was skipped",
              "symptom": "Gravy is thin and watery"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Replace the lid and return to a 160°C oven for a further 30-40 minutes. The potato top can be browned in a final blast at the end.",
              "cause": "Lamb shoulder varies; some pieces need longer",
              "symptom": "Lamb is still tough after 2 hours"
            },
            {
              "fix": "Cut a generous V into each kidney half to ensure the pale core is completely removed.",
              "cause": "The suet core was not fully removed",
              "symptom": "Kidneys taste harsh and bitter"
            }
          ]
        },
        "content": []
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Where this dish lives",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "text": "Lancashire hotpot is one of the most enduring dishes in British regional cooking. It was made by mill workers' wives who assembled the pot in the morning and left it in the bread oven to cook slowly through the day. The kidney is the traditional addition: a practical way of making the meat go further while adding flavour. Serve with pickled red cabbage, which cuts through the richness of the gravy.",
            "type": "text"
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
